  <h2>What Is a Black Hole?</h2>
  <p>
    A black hole is a region of spacetime where gravity is so strong that nothing can escape — not even light. They form when massive stars collapse under their own gravity.
  </p>

  <h2>The Event Horizon</h2>
  <p>
    The event horizon marks the boundary of no return. Once anything crosses it, escape becomes physically impossible.
  </p>

  <h2>Accretion Disks</h2>
  <p>
    Matter spiraling into a black hole forms a glowing disk of superheated gas. This is what telescopes actually observe — not the black hole itself.
  </p>

  <h2>Gravitational Lensing</h2>
  <p>
    Black holes warp spacetime, bending light and distorting the appearance of nearby stars and gas. This creates the iconic ring-like structures seen in many images.
  </p>

  <h2>Famous Black Holes</h2>
  <p>
    Sagittarius A* sits at the center of the Milky Way, while M87* became the first black hole ever imaged. These giants anchor galaxies and shape cosmic evolution.
  </p>
